article.headline: Hammon, not Weatherspoon, gets crunch-time minutes
article.linkText: Hammon sparks Liberty off bench with 21 points
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Liberty guard Becky Hammon finished the game on the floor, while starter Teresa Weatherspoon watched from the bench. Those endings are becoming more frequent. Hammon scored 21 points as the Liberty beat the Charlotte Sting 69-57 Sunday. The fourth-year player is a backup to Weatherspoon but is New York's emerging star. Weatherspoon had no points in 17 minutes, the fourth time this season she has not scored. In a 70-61 win over Sacramento last week, Hammon played the final 16 minutes and finished with 17 points while Weatherspoon stayed on the bench. Coach Richie Adubato called Hammon's play "another All-Star performance," but has no plans to make her the starter. "Right now I'd start the same team we did today," Adubato said. "It's a situation where you play who's really playing well. How do you take Becky out when she's scoring 21 points in 28 minutes?" Hammon went 6-of-8, including 3-of-4 from 3-point range. She also made all six of her free throws and had four rebounds and three assists. "I'm comfortable with my role right now," Hammon said. "It's an advantage to see the tempo and demeanor of our team. I just want to play." Crystal Robinson, Tamika Whitmore and Vickie Johnson each added 11 points for the Liberty, who started a four-game homestand with the victory. Andrea Stinson had 14 points, and Dawn Staley added 12 points and nine assists to lead Charlotte (6-5). Hammon again starred for the Liberty (5-4) and led a second-half comeback. After trailing 35-31 at halftime, Charlotte tied it at 40 six minutes into the second half. Adubato got a technical with 12:54 to play for arguing a non-foul call, and Charlotte scored the next four points to take a 44-40 lead. The Liberty were not about to let things unravel as they did against Detroit on Friday and Los Angeles last week when they blew second-half leads. Instead, Hammon led a huge spurt to close out the game. Down by two, Hammon had a steal and uncontested layup to start an 18-5 run that gave the Liberty a 63-52 lead with 2:38 to play, sealing the game. Charlotte shot just 33.3 percent from the field. "We didn't execute down the stretch," Sting coach Trudi Lacey said. "You have to hit big shots when you're playing away from home." Hammon led the Liberty with 13 points in the first half on 4-of-6 shooting. She came off the bench nine minutes into the game and scored seven straight points to help the Liberty overcome an early seven-point deficit. Even though her role is expanding, Hammon said she and Weatherspoon are still friends. "I'm Spoon's biggest fan," Hammon said. "We worked out all offseason together. She's been the leader of this team for seven, eight years. "She's been very supportive of this whole team and has handled everything that's been thrown at her like a champion. I admire her for that." Allison Feaster, the Sting's leading scorer, was held to two points in the first half. She finished with 11. Adubato credited Johnson and Robinson for their strong defense on Feaster and Stinson. Game notes
Weatherspoon and center Tari Phillips lead the Eastern Conference All-Star voting at their respective positions. Voting ends Tuesday, and the All-Star game is at Madison Square Garden on July 12. ... Entering the game against the Liberty, Charlotte ranked second in the league in points allowed a game (62).
